data = [[row['Lat'],row['Long']] for inde, row in sample.iterrows()]
## Counter for the day of week
countM = 0
countTu = 0
countW = 0
countTh = 0
countF = 0
countSa = 0
countSu = 0

## iterate through the row and mark it with different colors
for index, row in sample.iterrows():
    color = ''
    if row['DAY_OF_WEEK'] == 'Monday':
        color = 'black'
        countM += 1
    if row['DAY_OF_WEEK'] == 'Tuesday':
        color = 'yellow'
        countTu += 1        
    if row['DAY_OF_WEEK'] == 'Wednesday':
        color = 'red'
        countW += 1
    if row['DAY_OF_WEEK'] == 'Thursday':
        color = 'blue'
        countTh += 1
    if row['DAY_OF_WEEK'] == 'Friday':
        color = 'purple'
        countF += 1
    if row['DAY_OF_WEEK'] == 'Saturday':
        color = 'green'
        countSa += 1
    if row['DAY_OF_WEEK'] == 'Sunday':
        color = 'white'  
        countSu += 1
    
    folium.Circle(
    radius=20,
    location=[float(row['Lat']), float(row['Long'])],
    color=color,
    fill=True,).add_to(map_osm)
    
map_osm
print(countM)
print(countTu)
print(countW)
print(countTh)
print(countF)
print(countSa)
print(countSu)

The interactive map illustrates the sample of 300 random different crime incidents cases happened in Boston. On the map there are different color circles representing which day of the week the crime incidents happened. I assumed that there will me the most crime casses on the Weekends. However, the most common days of the week for crime are seen as Thursday and Friday. Typically Sunday had the least number of cases of the week. Even with the full dataset the result was the same. There were two areas in Boston where the dots were mostly concentrated. It was the downtown, specifically Roxbury and the north end of Boston. And when I searched the internet I found that Roxbury has 104% more crime than Boston overall.

map_osm2 = folium.Map(location=[42.36, -71.05], zoom_start=13)
countNight = 0
countMidnight = 0
countEven = 0

## sample on month 2
for index, boston in sample[sample["MONTH"] == 2].iterrows():
    ## Mark red for hours 19 and 20
    if boston["HOUR"] == 19 or boston["HOUR"] == 20:
        countNight += 1
        folium.Marker(location=[boston["Lat"], boston["Long"]],
                    icon=folium.Icon(color='red')).add_to(map_osm2)
             
    ## Mark blue for hours 2 and 3
    if boston["HOUR"] == 2 or boston["HOUR"] == 3:
        countMidnight += 1
        folium.Marker(location=[boston["Lat"], boston["Long"]],
            icon=folium.Icon(color='blue')).add_to(map_osm2)
     
    ## Mark green for hours 12 and 1
    if boston["HOUR"] == 12 or boston["HOUR"] == 1:
        countEven += 1
        folium.Marker(location=[boston["Lat"], boston["Long"]],
            icon=folium.Icon(color='green')).add_to(map_osm2)
        
        
print(countNight)
print(countMidnight)
print(countEven)
map_osm2

This map have markers with three different colors. The blue marker represents crime cases that happened during midnight. The red markers represent crime cases after at dinner time, and the green ones represent cases at lunch time. Since the dataset was too large, which makes the meaning of the markers meaningless and hard to see, I only chose the crimes that happened on Feburary. I didn't expect crime icidient whould be less cases during midnight compare to the other two time periods. I the number of crime cases during lunch time came out to be high which was also not expected.
